topic. Lemke explains that life has become an independent, objective and measurable factor as well as a collective reality that can be separated from concrete living beings and the singularity of individual experience. He shows how our understanding of the processes of life, the organizing of populations and the need to "govern" individuals and collectives lead to practices of correction, exclusion, normalization, and disciplining. In this lucidly written book, Lemke outlines the stakes and the debates surrounding biopolitics, providing a systematic overview of the history of the notion and making clear its relevance for sociological and contemporary theoretical debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBiopolitics. 4aHere. 4aLemke. 4abeen. 4abiopolitics. 4acontemporary. 4adebates. 4adecision-making. 4aeugenics. 4aeverything. 4aexploring. 4afrom. 4alife. 4alinked. 4amuch. 4aneeded. 4aoffers. 4aorganization. 4aoverview. 4aprimer. 4aproviding. 4aracism. 4arational. 4arelevance. 4asocial. 4asystematic. 4atheoretical. 4atopic. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aCasper, Monica J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMoore, Lisa Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814753378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814753378.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK